{
  "answer": "**In the *Yājñavalkya Smṛti* (Chapter 1), verse 1.66 (marked as \"Yj_1.66\") specifies rules on penalties related to marriage and brides:**\n\n> One who gives a maiden without disclosing her defects is to be fined the highest amercement. One who abandons a faultless wife is to be punished; one who falsely accuses her is to be fined one hundred.[^1]\n\nThis follows verse 1.65 (on giving away a maiden once, but allowing a better suitor) and precedes verse 1.67 (defining a \"remarried woman\" or *punarbhū* and a woman acting independently or *svairiṇī*); the context concerns marriage duties, giving brides, and spousal obligations.[^2]\n\n[^1]: *Yājñavalkya Smṛti*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6/01/translation/#p-1200e1).\n[^2]: *Yājñavalkya Smṛti*, [paragraphs](/works/unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6/01/translation/#p-5d34e9-p-53a45a).",
